english:
  title: A Record of the Restoration of Yinghu Pavilion
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yinghu was a celebrated tower of Yongga. Though its mountainous vistas, grand and wondrous, seemed to yield to the Chukseok of Jinju or the Yeongnam towers of Milyang, yet standing together on the banks of the Luo Water, those called the Tower of Viewing Waters in the Sangshan and the Moon Wave Pavilion in Ilseon could scarcely contest for pride of place with this tower.

    When the Goryeo King Gongmin fled southward to escape the Red Turban rebellion and dwelt in this region, he visited this tower and delighted in it. Upon his return to the capital, he wrote three great characters for the tower's nameplate with his own hand and bestowed them upon the people of the region. The magistrate Shin Ja-jeon enlarged the tower's structure to display it properly, and to this day it shines among the rafters and beams—a glory unknown to Chukseok or Yeongnam.

    More than a hundred years have passed since Shin Ja-jeon's work. In all that time, did no official oversee the repair of rotting pillars and crumbling walls? Yet human hearts have changed. Those who cultivate connections through gifts heed only their own gain, while those who merely maintain old forms lack leisure from their ledgers. Who would expend effort restoring what crumbles, squandering treasured wealth? Thus the tower's daily decay occasions no surprise.

    But now my contemporary, Magistrate Kim Jil of Jeonan, having risen from the Office of Remonstrance to govern this region, has in but a few years brought order to the land and harmony to the people. Year after year the harvests flourish. Even disputes over land and slaves—which once flooded the provincial office—now settle fairly, leaving both victor and vanquished content. The accumulated revenues have filled the treasury to overflowing.

    Magistrate Kim resolved with his officers and people to reconstruct this tower. In the third month of the year Mushin, he gathered willing workers and assigned duties fairly. Preserving the old foundation, he measured anew and made judicious additions, increasing the height and breadth by a third. The red and white decorations, the gold-leaf nameplate—all now gleam with renewed splendor. Within mere months the work was complete. The townsfolk, young and old alike, gazed upon it and marveled, declaring that divine assistance had blessed the work.

    The following spring, Magistrate Kim sent word requesting a record. I, unworthy though I am, gladly joined with the venerable Tham-am and Mog-eun to inscribe my name among the authors. Taking brush in hand, I reflect thus: "The magistrate governs with integrity and fairness, without harshness, ever guided by law. He regards those who seek favor through gifts as no better than beasts, and those who merely preserve old forms as mere servants. The people love and revere him as though Gong and Huang had returned a thousand years hence. Surely such a man has ample capacity to restore a single tower. Moreover, this region has long been known for its virtuous and simple customs, and its people are readily moved to right action. This restoration serves not idle pleasure, nor future fame, but only to preserve what was meant to endure."

    Yet I confess a deeper feeling stirs within me. In my youth, in the early years of Seonghua, I served in the military encampment at Ulsan for two periods. Often I journeyed through this region, and always I ascended this tower to wander in contemplation. To the east, thirty leagues distant, lay the realm of the Blue Waterfowl, where the auspicious clouds of the royal birthplace ascended to heaven—a blessing as enduring as that which graced the Zhou dynasty's sacred lineage. Ten leagues north rose Byeong Mountain, where the rebel Gyeon Hwon once held his thousand horsemen in the mountain passes before his collapse and death, when the righteous valor of the Wang clan blazed forth across the southeast. Westward, I gazed upon Pung Peak and lamented how Yuan Pong first showed loyalty then wavered, unable to share in the glory of the Six Great Generals. Southward, I beheld Gal Mountain's verdant slopes piercing the sky, its mists and clouds and grasses seeming to echo the residual grace of Kim Saeng's brushwork in full flourish. When my limbs grew weary, I would set out in a small boat, drifting along winding banks and shallow shoals, sometimes until deep night, returning only when the joy was spent. All the pavilion's wonders lay open before me, and I gained much from those days.

    Thirty years have passed, yet these memories still drift through my heart. Should Magistrate Kim's tenure be extended and my own journey southward come to pass, I would travel with a single servant and horse to visit the lake once more. There I would ascend this tower with the magistrate to speak of old times, and perhaps compose verses to add to the songs of praise the people sing.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gong and Huang refer to the renowned Han dynasty officials Gong Yu and Huang Ba, celebrated for their virtuous and effective governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Blue Waterfowl realm' (Cheongbu) refers to a region associated with royal ancestry and cosmic blessing in Korean historical tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: Gyeon Hwon was the founder of Later Baekje; his defeat by the Wang clan (which founded Goryeo) was a pivotal moment in Korean history.
  - key: ''
    value: Kim Saeng was a legendary calligrapher of the Silla period, known for his bold and dynamic brushwork style.
